  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "4:1-6 The strongest and best arguments against sin, are taken from the sufferings of Christ. He died to destroy sin; and though he cheerfully submitted to the worst sufferings, yet he never gave way to the least sin. Temptations could not prevail, were it not for man's own corruption; but true Christians make the will of God, not their own lust or desires, the rule of their lives and actions. And true conversion makes a marvellous change in the heart and life. It alters the mind, judgment, affections, and conversation. When a man is truly converted, it is very grievous to him to think how the time past of his life has been spent. One sin draws on another. Six sins are here mentioned which have dependence one upon another. It is a Christian's duty, not only to keep from gross wickedness, but also from things that lead to sin, or appear evil. The gospel had been preached to those since dead, who by the proud and carnal judgment of wicked men were condemned as evil-doers, some even suffering death. But being quickened to Divine life by the Holy Spirit, they lived to God as his devoted servants. Let not believers care, though the world scorns and reproaches them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Who shall give account - That is, they shall not do this with impunity. They are guilty in this of a groat wrong and they must answer for it to God.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That is ready to judge - That is, \"who is prepared to judge\" - τῷ ἑτοίμως ἔχοντι  tō hetoimōs echonti. See the phrase used in Acts 21:13; \"I am ready not to be bound only, but also to die at Jerusalem.\" 2 Corinthians 12:14; \"the third time I am ready to come to you.\" Compare the word \"ready\" - ἑτοιμος  hetoimos - in Matthew 22:4, Matthew 22:8; Matthew 24:44; Matthew 25:10; Luke 12:40; Luke 22:33; 1 Peter 1:5. The meaning is, not that he was about to do it, or that the day of judgment was near at hand - whatever the apostle may have supposed to be true on that point - but that he was prepared for it; all the arrangements were made with reference to it; there was nothing to hinder it.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "That is ready to judge - That is, \"who is prepared to judge\" - τῷ ἑτοίμως ἔχοντι  tō hetoimōs echonti. See the phrase used in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 21:13",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; \"I am ready not to be bound only, but also to die at Jerusalem.\" ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2 Corinthians 12:14",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; \"the third time I am ready to come to you.\" Compare the word \"ready\" - ἑτοιμος  hetoimos - in ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 22:4",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 22:8",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 24:44",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Matthew 25:10",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Luke 12:40",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Luke 22:33",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Peter 1:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". The meaning is, not that he was about to do it, or that the day of judgment was near at hand - whatever the apostle may have supposed to be true on that point - but that he was prepared for it; all the arrangements were made with reference to it; there was nothing to hinder it.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "To judge the quick and the dead - The living and the dead; that is, those who shall be alive when he comes, and those in their graves. This is a common phrase to denote all who shall be brought before the bar of God for judgment. See the Acts 10:42 note; 1 Thessalonians 4:16-17 notes; 2 Timothy 4:1 note. The meaning in this connection seems to be, that they should bear their trials and the opposition which they would meet with patiently, not feeling that they were forgotten, nor attempting to avenge themselves; for the Lord would vindicate them when he should come to judgment, and call those who had injured them to an account for all the wrongs which they had done to the children of God. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "To judge the quick and the dead - The living and the dead; that is, those who shall be alive when he comes, and those in their graves. This is a common phrase to denote all who shall be brought before the bar of God for judgment. See the ",
